  "footnotes": [
    "Tunis / North: Mediterranean-facing coast; Carthage (c.814 BCE) was founded by Phoenician settlers from Tyre according to tradition; became the greatest city in the western Mediterranean before its destruction by Rome in 146 BCE; modern Tunis grew on a nearby site",
    "Kairouan / South: inland agricultural heartland; Kairouan was founded in 670 CE as the first Arab city in the Maghreb and served as the capital of the Aghlabid dynasty; the Great Mosque of Kairouan is one of the oldest mosques in Africa",
    "Ifriqiya: the Arabic name for the province encompassing modern Tunisia and parts of Libya and Algeria; derived from the Roman name 'Africa'; under successive caliphates, Ifriqiya was the wealthiest province of the western Islamic world",
    "Aghlabid dynasty (800–909): founded by Ibrahim ibn al-Aghlab as an autonomous emirate under Abbasid suzerainty; conquered Sicily (827–902) and parts of southern Italy; their court was a center of Islamic learning and architecture",
    "Fatimid Caliphate (909–969 in Ifriqiya): the Ismaili Fatimids overthrew the Aghlabids; after conquering Egypt in 969, they relocated their capital to Cairo, leaving the Zirid dynasty as vassals in Ifriqiya",
    "Hafsid dynasty (1229–1574): the last major indigenous Maghrebi dynasty; claimed descent from the Almohad caliph; resisted Aragonese, Ottoman, and other external pressures for three centuries; finally conquered by the Ottomans",
    "Husainid dynasty (1705–1957): founded by Husayn ibn Ali al-Turki; governed Tunisia under nominal Ottoman suzerainty; negotiated the first constitution (Dustur) in the Arab world in 1861; survived as beys under French protectorate until Tunisian independence in 1956"
  ]
